          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Legitimacy questioned</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-30-2.jpg" alt="Legitimacy questioned" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Mikheil Kavelashvil, a former footballer and critic of the West, was <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-dec-2024-6-sworn-in" target="_blank">sworn in</a> as Georgia’s new president amid political turmoil. The former president, Salome Zourabichvili, denounced his legitimacy and refused to step down. She believes the alleged fraud in the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-dec-2024-7-october-parliamentary-election" target="_blank">October parliamentary election</a> secured his selection by lawmakers. Zourabichvili, a pro-EU leader, vowed to fight, accusing the ruling Georgian Dream party of sinking the country’s EU ambitions and steering it toward Russia.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Protests flared in Georgia’s capital, Tbilisi, over the ruling Georgian Dream party’s decision to freeze EU accession talks until 2028. Demonstrators held red cards and made fun of Kavelashvili’s sports career. <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-dec-2024-7a-the-protests" target="_blank">The protests</a> have been ongoing for over a month. The European Parliament has rejected the election results, urging a rerun, while the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-dec-2024-8-us-sanctioned" target="_blank">U.S. sanctioned</a> Georgian Dream's oligarch Bidzina Ivanishvili for undermining Georgia’s democratic future.​</p>
        </mj-text>
