          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Russia’s gas squeeze</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Gazprom announced it will halt <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-dec-2024-9-gas-supplies" target="_blank">gas supplies</a> to Transnistria, a Russian-occupied region in Moldova, starting New Year’s Day. The decision follows allegations that Moldovogaz failed to meet payment obligations. Moldovan Prime Minister Dorin Recean denied the claim and subsequently labeled it as Russia weaponizing energy to pressure the pro-Western Moldovan government. Meanwhile, alternative routes via TurkStream are available but rejected by Gazprom, intensifying the region's energy crisis.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Since 2022, Transnistria has relied exclusively on Russian gas, while the rest of Moldova has shifted to other supplies.Transnistria is Russia's hold on Moldova. The area has broken away to claim independence despite being <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-dec-2024-10-unrecognized" target="_blank">unrecognized</a>. The breakaway state has asked to be annexed by Russia despite claiming sovereignty.</p>
        </mj-text>
