          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Who is Laura Codruta Kovesi?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-30-3.jpg" alt="foundations" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-dec-2024-13-laura-codruta-kovesi" target="_blank">Laura Codruta Kovesi</a> is a renowned Romanian prosecutor for her leadership in anti-corruption efforts. From 2013 to 2018, she served as the Chief Prosecutor of the Romanian Anticorruption Directorate (DNA), where she led high-profile investigations into corruption, including cases involving senior politicians and officials. She has <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-dec-2024-13a-prosecuted" target="_blank">prosecuted</a> 68 high-level functionaries, including 53 deputies and 14 ministers from both houses of the government. 37 politicians were convicted before she was removed from the post by the Social Democrats, while other cases are still ongoing.​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Before her role at DNA, Kovesi was the Prosecutor General of Romania from 2006 to 2012, becoming the country’s first female and youngest prosecutor to hold that position. In 2019, Kovesi was appointed the first <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-dec-2024-14-european-chief-prosecutor" target="_blank">European Chief Prosecutor</a>, heading the newly established European Public Prosecutor's Office (EPPO), an EU body responsible for investigating and prosecuting financial crimes affecting the EU budget.​</p>
        </mj-text>
